            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 63-year-old woman from the Czech Republic who recently sought care after noticing a breast lump and mild swelling in one breast, along with intermittent nipple discharge that made her increasingly anxious about cancer [SNOMED:C50.9]. She says the change was first obvious while dressing and later while showering, when the area felt different from the surrounding tissue and somewhat irritated [SNOMED:C50.9]. She does not describe dramatic systemic illness, but the persistence of the breast change has been distressing and has disrupted her sleep and concentration [SNOMED:C50.9].\n\nShe lives with her husband and remains active in daily life, helping care for grandchildren and keeping a small garden. She previously worked in an administrative role and now spends much of her week between home responsibilities, walking in her neighborhood, and meeting a close circle of friends for coffee. Since noticing the breast change, she has become more withdrawn and checks the area repeatedly, worried by the lump and the occasional nipple discharge symptom [SNOMED:C50.9].\n\nIn conversation, {patientName} appears neatly dressed, cooperative, and worried but composed. She speaks clearly about her fear that a breast lump could represent a malignant condition and focuses on the local breast findings rather than generalized symptoms [SNOMED:C50.9]. Her family describes her as practical and dependable, and they have encouraged her to pursue imaging and biopsy promptly."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ecf40d7f-6218-4803-a443-31fc1c60fed0",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports that the current problem began with self-detection of a breast lump, followed by awareness of mild breast swelling and irritation, and she later noticed occasional nipple discharge [SNOMED:C50.9]. She denies a major traumatic explanation for the lump itself, although she understands that breast pain can occur in other settings and is worried because this change has persisted [MEDDIALOG:C50.9:5, SNOMED:C50.9].\n\nHer background history includes hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and type 2 diabetes treated chronically with oral medications. She has had no prior cancer diagnosis and no recent hospitalizations. She is a nonsmoker by history and drinks alcohol only occasionally. She is postmenopausal by age. The emotional strain of the possible diagnosis has increased her anxiety, but she remains independent in all daily activities."
          }
        ]
      }
